3ty.title: Fractional bits
3ty.text:
A message singling out one thing from a set of 8 carries $\log_2(8)=3$ [3p0 bits] of information. Similarly, a message singling out one thing from a set of 1024 carries 10 bits. How many bits does a message singling out one thing from a set of 3 carry? By the definition of "bit," the answers is $\log_2(3) \approx 1.58.$ What does this mean? That it takes about one and a half yes-or-no questions to single out one thing from a set of three? What is "half of a yes-or-no question"?

Fractional bits can be interpreted as telling about the [expectation expected] cost of transmitting information: If you want to single out one thing from a set of 3 using bits (in, e.g., the [+galcom] thought experiment) then you'll have to purchase two bits, but sometimes you'll be able to sell one of them back. If you transmit lots and lots of information, then each message singling out one thing from a set of 3 will cost you 1.58 bits on average, if you encode your message as cleverly as possible. For more on this interpretation, see [+fractional_bits_as_expected_cost].

Fractional bits can also be interpreted as conversion rates between types of information: "A message singling out one thing from three carries about 1.58 bits" can be interpreted as "one [trit] is worth about 1.58 bits." To understand this, see [ Converting between units of information], or just [ How many bits is a trit worth?]

Fractional units of information can also be interpreted as a measure of how much we're using the digits allocated to encoding a number. For example, working with fractional [decit decits] instead of fractional bits, a message singling out one thing from 500 requires three digits to write down, but only carries about 2.70 decits of information, because 500 isn't using all three of those digits to their fullest extent. To see that, note that we could declare "all numbers that start with a number $n \ge 5$ will be interpreted as if they start with the number $n - 5.$" Then, because we have two ways of representing each number, we can encode one extra bit into our message (according to whether we use the low representation or the high representation of the intended number), so the amount of information in 500 should be one bit lower than the amount of information in 1000 — in other words, the amount of information in a message singling out one thing from among 500 should be 3 decits minus one bit, which comes out to about 2.70 decits (or just short of 9 bits). For more on this interpretation, see [+3v3].
